{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":967,"record_hash":"sha256:b161cd23d1db512bcd1ecb8ec512805cb2c915347145ee16d0b1ffc0b54bd9b3","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:13:12.330Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: agent-trail.md\n@@\n Recommended v1 architecture:\n \n ```text\n web/API facade -> generator HTTP API -> one generator process\n                                   -> one mounted persistent volume\n ```\n+\n+Decision after parallel storage research: use **Fly Machine + Fly Volume** for\n+the first production deployment unless there is already a stronger organizational\n+reason to choose another platform. It is the lightest path that still gives Git\n+and SQLite normal local filesystem behavior.\n+\n+Acceptable development/spike shortcut:\n+\n+```text\n+generator process -> ephemeral local scratch -> projection JSON response/cache\n+```\n+\n+Use that only to prove the projection pipeline and measure cold-generation time.\n+Do not treat it as the product architecture unless cold generation is proven\n+cheap enough and stable enough for reviewer-facing latency.\n@@\n Use object storage only for backups, exported projection JSON, or archived\n snapshots. Do not try to run the live Git object database or GitMeta SQLite\n state directly on S3/R2/Tigris-style object storage.\n@@\n - SQLite's WAL documentation says all processes using a database must be on the\n   same host and WAL does not work over a network filesystem\n   ([SQLite WAL](https://www.sqlite.org/wal.html)). Avoid clever shared-network\n   filesystem designs unless there is a strong reason.\n+- Git's FAQ warns against syncing active repositories file-by-file through cloud\n+  sync tools because refs and objects can become inconsistent\n+  ([Git FAQ](https://git-scm.com/docs/gitfaq.html)).\n+- S3 mount layers are not a substitute for a real filesystem. AWS Mountpoint for\n+  S3 does not support file locking, symlinks, or modifying existing files, which\n+  disqualifies it for live Git/SQLite state\n+  ([Mountpoint for S3](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)).\n \n-Lightweight hosting options that fit:\n+Recommended hosting path:\n \n - Fly.io Machine + Fly Volume. Fly volumes are local persistent storage for Fly\n-  Machines and get daily snapshots\n-  ([Fly volumes](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/)).\n+  Machines, mount like a regular directory, are tied one-to-one to a Machine,\n+  and get daily snapshots\n+  ([Fly volumes](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/),\n+  [Fly snapshots](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/snapshots/)).\n+- Run one Rust HTTP worker in a Docker image with `git` installed.\n+- Mount the volume at `/data` or `/var/lib/agent-trail`.\n+- Start with one Machine and one Volume. Let the single-volume constraint be the\n+  single-writer guarantee.\n+- Use Fly autostart/autostop only if generation is purely request/response. If\n+  queued background jobs are added, keep one Machine running.\n+\n+Good alternates:\n+\n - Render background worker or private service + persistent disk. Render supports\n-  disks for paid services and background workers\n-  ([Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks)).\n+  disks for paid services and background workers, but disks disable\n+  zero-downtime deploys. That is acceptable for v1 if the generator API handles\n+  retryable busy/down states\n+  ([Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks),\n+  [Render deploys](https://render.com/docs/deploys)).\n - Railway service + volume. Railway volumes mount persistent read/write storage\n-  into a service\n-  ([Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes)).\n+  into a service; replicas cannot be used with volumes, which again fits the\n+  one-writer model\n+  ([Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes),\n+  [Railway volume reference](https://docs.railway.com/reference/volumes)).\n \n-AWS can solve this, but it is heavier than needed for v1. Lambda/ECS can mount\n-EFS ([Lambda EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html),\n-[ECS EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)),\n-but that introduces VPC, mount targets, IAM, throughput modes, network\n-filesystem semantics, and more operational surface. Use it only if the rest of\n-the product is already committed to AWS.\n+AWS path if needed:\n+\n+- Prefer EC2 + EBS for the live cache. EBS is durable block storage that can be\n+  mounted and used like normal disk\n+  ([EBS volumes](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/ebs/latest/userguide/ebs-volumes.html)).\n+- ECS/Fargate with ephemeral storage plus object-storage result cache is a valid\n+  measurement spike, not the default product architecture\n+  ([Fargate task storage](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)).\n+- Lambda + EFS and ECS + EFS can work technically, but they introduce VPC, mount\n+  targets, IAM, throughput modes, network filesystem semantics, and more\n+  operational surface. Use them only if the product is already committed to AWS\n+  ([Lambda EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html),\n+  [ECS EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)).\n@@\n Concurrency model:\n \n - Start with one generator process attached to one volume.\n - Use a per-repository lock around repo initialization, fetch, GitMeta\n   materialization, and projection.\n+- Disable automatic Git maintenance for cached repos (`gc.auto=0`) and run\n+  maintenance only inside the per-repository lock.\n - Do not let multiple generator instances write the same repository cache.\n - If more capacity is needed, shard repositories across workers by GitHub repo\n   id, or put generation jobs in a queue and route each repo to one owner worker.\n - The web/API facade should not mount or inspect the repository volume.\n@@\n Backup policy:\n \n - For v1, rely on provider volume snapshots plus the fact that repo caches are\n   rebuildable.\n - If generator-local SQLite becomes important, add a real SQLite backup path\n   rather than copying live database files. Litestream can replicate SQLite to\n-  S3-compatible storage ([Litestream](https://litestream.io/getting-started/)).\n+  S3-compatible storage ([Litestream](https://litestream.io/getting-started/)).\n+  SQLite's online backup API is also the correct primitive for live database\n+  copies ([SQLite Backup API](https://www.sqlite.org/backup.html)).\n+- If warm Git cache backup becomes important, produce it under the repo lock with\n+  Git-native tools such as `git bundle`; do not `cp -r` a live repository during\n+  fetch or maintenance ([git-bundle](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-bundle.html)).\n - Do not back up huge live Git caches unless there is measured evidence that\n   warm-cache loss is painful.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:13:12.330Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}